---
import CalcolatoreLayout from '../../layouts/CalcolatoreLayout.astro';
import Forfettari from '../../components/calcolatori/Forfettari';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
import { canonicalURL } from '../../lib/seo';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = "Regime Forfettario Calculator 2026: Flat Tax for P.IVA";
const description = "Calculate your taxes under Italy's flat-rate regime for freelancers. 5% or 15% substitute tax, INPS contributions, profitability coefficients, and net income.";
const canonical = canonicalURL('/en/flat-rate-regime-calculator/');

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'Flat-Rate Regime Calculator', url: canonical },
];
---

<CalcolatoreLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  calculatorName="Flat-Rate Regime Calculator"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  canonical={canonical}
  lang={lang}
>
  <Forfettari client:load lang={lang} />

  <Fragment slot="come-si-calcola">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      How taxes are calculated under the regime forfettario (flat-rate tax regime)
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The <strong>regime forfettario</strong> (flat-rate tax regime) is Italy's
        simplified and preferential tax scheme designed for freelancers, sole
        proprietors, and self-employed professionals (holders of a Partita IVA,
        i.e. a VAT number / freelancer registration) whose annual revenues do
        not exceed 85,000 euros. If you are an expat working as a freelancer in
        Italy or considering opening a Partita IVA, this regime is very likely
        the most tax-efficient option available to you in the first years of
        your activity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike the regime ordinario (standard tax regime), where taxable income
        is calculated analytically by subtracting actual documented expenses from
        revenues, the regime forfettario uses a <strong>coefficiente di
        redditivita'</strong> (profitability coefficient) to determine your
        taxable base. This coefficient is a fixed percentage set by law,
        assigned according to your codice ATECO (the Italian classification code
        for economic activities). It represents the presumed share of your
        revenue that constitutes profit. The remaining portion (100% minus the
        coefficient) is automatically treated as deductible costs -- you do not
        need to document or justify these costs individually. On the taxable
        income determined in this way, an <strong>imposta sostitutiva</strong>
        (substitute tax) is applied, which replaces IRPEF (personal income tax),
        regional and municipal surcharges, and IRAP (regional production tax).
      </p>
      <h3>Imposta sostitutiva (substitute tax): 5% or 15%</h3>
      <p>
        The standard rate of the imposta sostitutiva is <strong>15%</strong>.
        However, for the first five years of a new business activity, a reduced
        rate of <strong>5%</strong> applies, provided that the taxpayer has not
        carried out the same or a substantially similar activity as a
        self-employed person in the three years preceding the start of the new
        activity. This "startup" benefit is particularly attractive for expats
        who are beginning their freelance career in Italy for the first time.
        After the five-year period expires, the rate automatically reverts to
        15%. There is no application or approval process -- the rate change
        happens by operation of law.
      </p>
      <h3>Contributi previdenziali (social security contributions)</h3>
      <p>
        In addition to the imposta sostitutiva, every Partita IVA holder in Italy
        must pay mandatory social security contributions to INPS (the Italian
        national social security institute). The amount you pay depends on which
        INPS fund you belong to. Most freelancers and professionals without a
        dedicated professional pension fund (cassa previdenziale) are enrolled in
        the <strong>Gestione Separata INPS</strong>, where the contribution rate
        for 2026 is <strong>26.07%</strong> of taxable income (for those not
        enrolled in any other pension scheme). Artisans (artigiani) and traders
        (commercianti) pay contributions to their respective INPS funds, which
        have different rates and include a mandatory minimum annual contribution
        regardless of income. An important detail: social security contributions
        paid during the year are the <strong>only deduction</strong> allowed
        under the regime forfettario -- they reduce the taxable income on which
        the substitute tax is calculated the following year.
      </p>
      <h3>Profitability coefficients by ATECO code</h3>
      <p>
        The coefficiente di redditivita' (profitability coefficient) is the
        cornerstone of the regime forfettario: it determines what percentage of
        your gross revenue is treated as taxable income. The remaining share
        (100% minus the coefficient) represents the flat-rate deduction for
        costs that the law presumes you incur. The Italian legislature
        established differentiated coefficients for each economic sector, based
        on statistical analyses of average cost structures. Below are the main
        coefficients grouped by activity type:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trade intermediaries (intermediari del commercio): 86%.</strong> This is the highest coefficient because intermediation activities involve very low operating costs -- no warehousing, no inventory of goods. Only 14% of revenue is recognized as a flat-rate cost deduction.</li>
        <li><strong>Professionals (lawyers, consultants, IT, engineers): 78%.</strong> This is the standard coefficient for those working in professional services and intellectual activities. It covers software developers, business consultants, accountants, and all professions classified under ATECO groups 69-74. For most expat freelancers in tech, design, marketing, or consulting, this is the coefficient that applies.</li>
        <li><strong>Personal services (hairdressers, beauticians): 67%.</strong> A mid-range coefficient reflecting higher costs compared to pure professional services, due to consumable products, equipment, and premises rental.</li>
        <li><strong>Wholesale and retail trade: 40%.</strong> The lowest coefficient, reflecting the high cost of goods sold. However, for non-food wholesale trade, the coefficient rises to 62%.</li>
        <li><strong>Construction and real estate: 62%.</strong> A value accounting for the costs of materials, subcontracting, and equipment typical of the construction sector and property management activities.</li>
        <li><strong>Accommodation and food services (restaurants, hotels): 40%.</strong> The low coefficient recognizes the significant costs related to food raw materials, premises rental, utilities, and staff in the hospitality sector.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Choosing the correct codice ATECO when registering your Partita IVA is
        critical, because the coefficient directly affects your tax burden. An
        incorrect classification can lead to paying more tax than necessary or,
        worse, to disputes with the Agenzia delle Entrate (Italian Revenue
        Agency). If your activity spans multiple ATECO codes, the coefficient
        applied is the one corresponding to the activity that generates the
        majority of your revenue.
      </p>
      <h3>Flat-rate regime vs. standard regime: which is better?</h3>
      <p>
        The choice between the regime forfettario and the regime ordinario
        (standard tax regime) is one of the most important tax decisions for
        anyone holding a Partita IVA in Italy. There is no universal answer --
        the optimal choice depends on the actual cost structure of your business
        and your personal circumstances. Here are the key scenarios.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>When the flat-rate regime is more advantageous:</strong> the
        regime forfettario is beneficial when your actual business costs are
        lower than the flat-rate deduction recognized by the coefficient. For
        example, if you are an IT professional with a 78% coefficient, the tax
        system recognizes 22% of your revenue as costs. If your real expenses
        (software subscriptions, hardware, training courses, coworking space)
        amount to less than 22% of your revenue, the flat-rate regime is the
        better choice. Furthermore, the 15% substitute tax rate (or 5% for
        startups) is typically much lower than the marginal IRPEF rate under
        the standard regime, which can reach 43% for income exceeding 50,000
        euros. For a freelancer with low expenses and average revenue, the
        annual savings can exceed 5,000 to 10,000 euros compared to the
        standard regime.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>When the standard regime is more advantageous:</strong> the
        regime ordinario becomes preferable when you have significant real costs
        that exceed the flat-rate deduction. If you manage a business with
        employees, rent an expensive office, purchase merchandise or machinery,
        the analytical deduction of actual costs can reduce the taxable base far
        more than the profitability coefficient does. Additionally, under the
        standard regime you can benefit from all personal tax deductions
        (detrazioni) -- medical expenses, mortgage interest, dependent children
        allowances, home renovation bonuses -- which are <strong>not
        available</strong> under the regime forfettario. This aspect is often
        underestimated but can make a difference of thousands of euros,
        especially if you have a mortgage on your primary residence or
        dependent children.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The break-even analysis:</strong> the break-even point is
        calculated by comparing the total tax burden under both regimes. Take
        your gross revenue, compute the flat-rate taxable income (revenue times
        the coefficient) and the standard taxable income (revenue minus actual
        costs minus deductions). Then apply the respective taxes: the substitute
        tax for the forfettario, and IRPEF brackets plus surcharges for the
        ordinario. For a professional with a 78% coefficient, the break-even
        point generally occurs when actual costs exceed 35-40% of revenue, but
        this figure varies depending on income level and applicable personal
        deductions.
      </p>
      <h3>Electronic invoicing obligation (fatturazione elettronica)</h3>
      <p>
        Since January 1, 2024, the obligation to issue electronic invoices
        (fatturazione elettronica) has been extended to <strong>all</strong>
        taxpayers under the regime forfettario, with no remaining exemption
        thresholds. Previously, forfettari with revenues below 25,000 euros were
        exempt, but this exemption has been permanently removed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Electronic invoicing is carried out through the Sistema di Interscambio
        (SDI), the platform managed by the Agenzia delle Entrate that receives,
        validates, and forwards invoices in XML format to the recipient. To issue
        electronic invoices, you must use compatible invoicing software. Free
        options exist (such as the "Fatture e Corrispettivi" portal provided by
        the Agenzia delle Entrate), alongside commercial paid solutions that
        offer additional features like automatic numbering, digital archiving
        (archiviazione sostitutiva), and accounting integration. Popular
        third-party services used by expats include Finom, Fatture in Cloud, and
        Fiscozen, which often provide English-language interfaces.
      </p>
      <p>
        The electronic invoice format is FatturaPA (with an .xml extension),
        conforming to the technical specifications defined by the Agenzia delle
        Entrate. Each invoice must contain the recipient's SDI destination code
        (codice destinatario) or certified email address (PEC), the tax details
        of both the sender and recipient, the nature of the transaction (N2.2
        for operations under the regime forfettario, as they are VAT-exempt),
        the amount, and the description of the service or good provided. For
        forfettari, the invoice must include the mandatory wording prescribed by
        Article 1, paragraph 63 of Law 190/2014, indicating that no VAT is
        charged and no withholding tax (ritenuta d'acconto) applies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Penalties for failure to issue an electronic invoice or for late
        issuance range from 5% to 10% of the undocumented amounts, with a
        minimum of 500 euros per violation. For late issuance (beyond 12 days
        from the date of the transaction), the penalty is reduced if the
        taxpayer voluntarily regularizes within the deadlines allowed by
        ravvedimento operoso (voluntary correction with reduced penalties). It
        is therefore essential to have a reliable invoicing system in place and
        to respect issuance deadlines.
      </p>
      <h3>Key considerations for expats and non-Italian freelancers</h3>
      <p>
        If you are relocating to Italy and plan to work as a freelancer, there
        are several practical points to keep in mind regarding the regime
        forfettario. First, to access this regime you must be a <strong>tax
        resident in Italy</strong> -- meaning you spend more than 183 days per
        year in Italy or have your primary domicile or center of vital interests
        here. Second, the regime forfettario <strong>cannot be combined</strong>
        with the regime impatriati (the special tax regime for inbound workers),
        so you must choose one or the other. The impatriati regime may be more
        beneficial for employees or high-earning freelancers, while the
        forfettario is generally better for freelancers with moderate income and
        low actual costs. Third, even though you operate under the flat-rate
        regime and do not charge VAT on your invoices, when you invoice clients
        in other EU countries you still need to be aware of reverse charge
        mechanisms and may need to register for VIES (VAT Information Exchange
        System) to perform intra-EU transactions. Consulting with an Italian
        commercialista (chartered accountant) who has experience with
        international clients is strongly recommended before making your choice.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="valori">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      Taxes under the flat-rate regime: practical examples by revenue level
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The table below provides a summary of the tax calculation for a
        professional enrolled in the Gestione Separata INPS (profitability
        coefficient of 78%, contribution rate of 26.07%) with an imposta
        sostitutiva (substitute tax) rate of 15%. The INPS contribution amounts
        shown are calculated on the flat-rate taxable income and do not account
        for the deduction of prior-year contributions, for simplicity of
        presentation.
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="min-w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600">
              <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Annual revenue</th>
              <th class="text-right py-2 px-4 font-semibold">Taxable income (78%)</th>
              <th class="text-right py-2 px-4 font-semibold">Tax at 15%</th>
              <th class="text-right py-2 px-4 font-semibold">Tax at 5% (startup)</th>
              <th class="text-right py-2 pl-4 font-semibold">INPS (26.07%)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">30,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">23,400 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">3,510 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">1,170 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 pl-4">~6,100 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">50,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">39,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">5,850 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">1,950 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 pl-4">~10,168 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-2 pr-4">85,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">66,300 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">9,945 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 px-4">3,315 &euro;</td>
              <td class="text-right py-2 pl-4">~17,284 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        <strong>Comparison: 15% rate vs. 5% startup rate:</strong> the
        difference between the two rates becomes increasingly significant as
        revenue grows. At 30,000 euros of revenue, the difference is 2,340 euros
        per year (3,510 minus 1,170). At 85,000 euros of revenue, the startup
        savings reach 6,630 euros per year. Over the five years that the reduced
        rate applies, a professional with average revenue of 50,000 euros can
        save approximately 19,500 euros in total compared to the standard 15%
        rate.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Effective tax rate analysis:</strong> the overall tax burden
        (imposta sostitutiva plus INPS contributions) takes a substantial share
        of gross revenue. At 50,000 euros of revenue with the 15% rate, the
        total of substitute tax (5,850 euros) plus INPS contributions (~10,168
        euros) amounts to approximately 16,018 euros, equivalent to roughly 32%
        of gross revenue. With the 5% startup rate, the total drops to
        approximately 12,118 euros, or about 24.2% of gross revenue. These
        figures do not include the cost of mandatory professional pension funds
        (casse previdenziali) for regulated professions (lawyers, engineers,
        architects), which replace the Gestione Separata with their own rates
        and rules. For an unregulated professional with revenue of 85,000 euros,
        the net disposable income after taxes and contributions is approximately
        57,771 euros with the 15% rate, and approximately 64,401 euros with the
        5% startup rate.
      </p>
      <h3>Understanding the numbers: a step-by-step worked example</h3>
      <p>
        To make the calculation fully transparent, here is a step-by-step
        example for an expat freelance software developer invoicing 60,000 euros
        per year, enrolled in the Gestione Separata INPS, in their second year
        of activity (qualifying for the 5% startup rate), and assuming they paid
        8,000 euros in INPS contributions the previous year:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Step 1 -- Flat-rate taxable income:</strong> 60,000 euros x 78% = 46,800 euros.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2 -- Deduct prior-year INPS contributions:</strong> 46,800 - 8,000 = 38,800 euros (adjusted taxable income).</li>
        <li><strong>Step 3 -- Imposta sostitutiva at 5%:</strong> 38,800 x 5% = 1,940 euros.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 4 -- Current-year INPS contributions (Gestione Separata at 26.07%):</strong> 46,800 x 26.07% = approximately 12,201 euros.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 5 -- Total tax and contributions for the year:</strong> 1,940 + 12,201 = 14,141 euros.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 6 -- Net income:</strong> 60,000 - 14,141 = approximately 45,859 euros, or about 76.4% of gross revenue.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This example illustrates why the regime forfettario is so popular among
        freelancers in Italy: even with social security contributions factored
        in, the effective tax rate is significantly lower than what most
        employees face under the standard IRPEF brackets.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="faq">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      Frequently asked questions
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          What is the revenue limit for the regime forfettario?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The annual revenue (ricavi or compensi) limit to access and remain in the regime forfettario is 85,000 euros. If you exceed this threshold but stay below 100,000 euros, you exit the flat-rate regime starting from the following calendar year. If you exceed 100,000 euros during the current year, the exit is immediate: you must switch to the standard tax regime (regime ordinario) and apply VAT, IRPEF, and full accounting obligations from that point onward.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          What are the coefficienti di redditivita' (profitability coefficients)?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The coefficienti di redditivita' are fixed percentages established by Italian law that determine what portion of your gross revenue is treated as taxable income. For example, the coefficient for professionals is 78%, meaning that on 50,000 euros of revenue, the taxable income will be 39,000 euros. The remaining 22% is automatically recognized as business costs without requiring documentation. Coefficients range from 40% (food retail) to 86% (trade intermediaries), depending on the ATECO code assigned to your business activity.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Is the flat-rate regime better than the standard regime (regime ordinario)?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          It depends on your specific situation. The regime forfettario is advantageous when your actual business costs are lower than the flat-rate deduction (i.e., 100% minus the profitability coefficient). If you have substantial costs (office rent, employees, merchandise purchases), the standard regime may result in lower taxes because you can deduct actual expenses. Additionally, under the flat-rate regime you cannot claim personal tax deductions (detrazioni) such as mortgage interest, medical expenses, or dependent family member allowances, which can represent significant savings under the standard regime.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Can I deduct INPS contributions under the flat-rate regime?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes. Mandatory social security contributions (contributi previdenziali obbligatori) paid during the year are the only deduction permitted under the regime forfettario. They are subtracted from the flat-rate taxable income before the imposta sostitutiva (substitute tax) is applied. In practice, this means the INPS contributions you paid in the previous year reduce the taxable base for the current year, resulting in a lower substitute tax bill.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Do I need to charge VAT on my invoices under the flat-rate regime?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          No. Taxpayers under the regime forfettario do not charge VAT (IVA) on their invoices and do not have the right to deduct VAT on purchases. Invoices must include the specific exemption wording required by law (referencing Article 1, paragraph 63 of Law 190/2014). However, you are still required to issue electronic invoices (fatturazione elettronica) through the Sistema di Interscambio (SDI). This means your clients receive invoices without VAT, which can be either an advantage (lower prices for end consumers) or a disadvantage (business clients in the standard regime cannot reclaim VAT on your invoices).
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          What are the requirements to access the regime forfettario in 2026?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          To access the regime forfettario in 2026, you must meet several requirements. Your revenue in the previous year must not exceed 85,000 euros. You must not have incurred expenses for employees or collaborators exceeding 20,000 euros gross per year. You must not hold ownership interests (partecipazioni) in partnerships (societa' di persone), professional associations, or SRLs (limited liability companies) carrying out activities related to yours. You must not have received employment income or similar income (redditi da lavoro dipendente o assimilati) exceeding 35,000 euros in the previous year, unless the employment relationship has ended. Finally, you must not use special VAT schemes and must not exclusively sell real estate or building land.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How does the transition from flat-rate to standard regime work?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The transition depends on how much you exceed the revenue threshold. If your revenues surpass 85,000 euros but remain below 100,000 euros, you exit the regime forfettario starting from the following year -- for the current year, you continue to apply the flat-rate rules normally. If, however, you exceed 100,000 euros during the current year, the exit is immediate: from that point onward you must apply the standard regime with VAT, IRPEF, and full double-entry bookkeeping. In both cases, you will need to update your invoicing (adding VAT), open accounting books, and comply with all the obligations of the regime ordinario. You may re-enter the regime forfettario in subsequent years if you once again meet all the eligibility requirements.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Can INPS contributions be reduced under the flat-rate regime?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          A 35% reduction in INPS contributions is available exclusively for artisans (artigiani) and traders (commercianti) enrolled in their respective INPS funds. This benefit reduces both the fixed minimum contributions and the contributions calculated on income exceeding the minimum threshold. The reduction must be explicitly requested through the INPS online portal by February 28 of each year. Important: freelancers enrolled in the Gestione Separata INPS (which includes most professionals without a dedicated pension fund) are not eligible for this reduction. Furthermore, the contribution reduction results in proportionally reduced pension credit accrual -- you accumulate less contributory seniority, which may negatively impact your future pension entitlement.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Can I use the regime forfettario if I also have employment income?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes, but with limitations. You can hold a Partita IVA under the regime forfettario while also being employed, provided your employment income (redditi da lavoro dipendente o assimilati) did not exceed 35,000 euros gross in the previous year. If the employment relationship has ceased, this limit does not apply. This makes the flat-rate regime accessible to many expats who have a part-time employment contract while freelancing on the side, as long as their salary stays below the threshold. Note that your employment income and your freelance income are taxed separately: employment income follows the standard IRPEF rules, while freelance income follows the flat-rate regime rules.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Can I combine the regime forfettario with the regime impatriati?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          No, the two regimes are mutually exclusive. The regime impatriati (inbound workers tax regime) provides a partial exemption on IRPEF for individuals who transfer their tax residence to Italy, but it operates within the standard tax regime. Since the regime forfettario replaces IRPEF with the imposta sostitutiva, the IRPEF exemption offered by the impatriati regime has no effect. If you qualify for both, you must carefully evaluate which regime results in a lower overall tax burden for your specific income level and cost structure. Generally, the forfettario is better for lower incomes with few costs, while the impatriati regime is more advantageous for higher incomes or when you have significant deductible expenses.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

